        {
          "id": 70540,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Pituitary</span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 70541,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Thyroid</span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 70542,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Parathyroid</span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 70543,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Pineal Gland</span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">A 55-year-old woman presents with complaints of Fatigue, Bone Pain, and frequent Headaches. Her medical history is significant for recurrent kidney stones. On examination, her blood pressure is elevated. Laboratory tests reveal hypercalcemia.&nbsp; Biopsy of the gland is done in which oxyphil cells increased in number. Where these oxyphil cells are found?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q9114645",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 29573,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        3
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ans. C) Parathyroid</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option C:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Oxyphil cells&nbsp;</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">are found in the <strong>parathyroid gland</strong>.</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">They are less common than the <strong>chief cells</strong> of the <strong>parathyroid</strong> but can <strong>increase</strong> in <strong>number</strong> in certain conditions, such as <strong>parathyroid adenoma</strong> or <strong>hyperplasia</strong>, both of which can cause <strong>primary hyperparathyroidism</strong>. </span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">This condition is characterized by <strong>hypercalcemia</strong>, which can lead to symptoms such as <strong>bone pain</strong>, <strong>kidney stones</strong>, <strong>fatigue</strong>, and <strong>headaches</strong>, as seen in the patient&#39;s presentation. The <strong>elevated parathyroid hormone levels</strong> and <strong>hypercalcemia</strong> suggest a <strong>parathyroid gland disorder</strong>, likely involving the <strong>oxyphil cells</strong>.</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><br />\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/02/13/picture29.jpg\" style=\"height:357px; width:700px\" /><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option A.&nbsp;</span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">The pituitary gland, or <strong>hypophysis</strong>, is a <strong>major endocrine gland</strong> involved in regulating various hormones. It contains <strong>cell types</strong> such as <strong>somatotrophs</strong>, <strong>lactotrophs</strong>, <strong>corticotrophs</strong>, <strong>thyrotrophs</strong>, and <strong>gonadotrophs</strong>, but oxyphil cells are not typically found in the pituitary gland.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option B.&nbsp;</span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">The thyroid gland produces hormones like <strong>thyroxine</strong> (T4) and <strong>triiodothyronine</strong> (T3) that <strong>regulate metabolism</strong>. The <strong>thyroid</strong> contains <strong>follicular cells</strong> and <strong>parafollicular cells</strong> (<strong>C cells</strong>). Parafollicular cells secrete <strong>calcitonin</strong>, which is involved in <strong>calcium homeostasis</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option D</span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">. The pineal gland produces <strong>melatonin</strong>, a hormone that <strong>regulates</strong> <strong>sleep patterns</strong>. The pineal gland is known for <strong>pineaocytes</strong> (cells that produce <strong>melatonin</strong>) and other supporting cells, but it does not contain oxyphil cells.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Oxyphil cells</span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> are found in the <strong>parathyroid glands</strong>. These glands are <strong>small endocrine</strong> <strong>glands</strong> in the <strong>neck</strong> that <strong>produce parathyroid hormone (PTH)</strong>, which <strong>regulates calcium levels</strong> in the <strong>blood</strong>. </span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Oxyphil cells are distinct from the <strong>chief cells</strong>, which are the <strong>primary cells</strong> responsible for <strong>PTH production</strong>. The function of oxyphil cells is not entirely clear, but they increase in number with age.</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: Histology, Text and Atlas Brijesh Kumar Page No. 323</span></strong></span></span></p>",
