        {
          "id": 70632,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Hypocalcemia is a feature of Tetany</span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 70633,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">The Superior Parathyroid gland lies ventral to recurrent Laryngeal Nerve </span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 70634,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">The patient&rsquo;s Parathyroid glands were inadvertently removed during total Thyroidectomy </span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 70635,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">The position of Inferior Parathyroid gland is variable</span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">A 45-year-old male underwent total thyroidectomy. Four days after the surgery the patient complained of altered sensation around the mouth followed by tingling and numbness in fingers and toes and painful cramps on hands and feet. Which of the following statements is incorrect?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q7437422",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 29572,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        3
      ],
      "solution": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ans. B) The Superior Parathyroid Gland lies ventral to recurrent Laryngeal Nerve</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option B:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">The superior parathyroid gland lies <strong>dorsal to recurrent laryngeal nerves.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/02/17/picture28.jpg\" style=\"height:761px; width:600px\" /></strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option A.&nbsp;</span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Tetany, which is <strong>characterized</strong> by symptoms like <strong>tingling, numbness,</strong> and <strong>muscle cramps</strong>, is often a result of <strong>hypocalcemia</strong>. This condition can occur after <strong>total thyroidectomy</strong> due to <strong>inadvertent removal</strong> or damage to the <strong>parathyroid glands</strong>, which <strong>regulate calcium levels</strong> in the <strong>body</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option C.&nbsp;</span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">During <strong>total thyroidectomy,</strong> there is a risk of <strong>inadvertently</strong> <strong>removing</strong> or damaging the <strong>parathyroid glands</strong>, leading to <strong>hypocalcemia</strong> and <strong>subsequent tetany</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option D.&nbsp;</span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">The <strong>position</strong> of the <strong>inferior parathyroid glands</strong> is known to be more <strong>variable</strong> than the <strong>superior glands</strong>, which can pose a <strong>challenge</strong> during <strong>thyroid surgery</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">&nbsp;The <strong>superior parathyroid glands</strong> are typically located <strong>dorsal (posterior)</strong> to the <strong>recurrent laryngeal nerve</strong>, not ventral (anterior). This anatomical relationship is <strong>important </strong>during <strong>thyroid surgery </strong>to avoid <strong>damage</strong> to the <strong>parathyroid glands.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: Gray&rsquo;s Anatomy 41<sup>st</sup> Edition Pg no 471</span></strong></span></span></p>",
